[page]44|MS-DAVY-12001-000-00044|dnp20a044pp|70523532[/page]
The changes
The perfection of chemical science
Nothing perhaps is more absurd in the present
state of our knowledge than to connect
scientific generalisations of the phaenomena
of life, with the common & simple
changes [deletion]taking place in our organs[/deletion]. -
perpetually taking place on our globe. -
The rapid changes in our organs connected
with perceptions & muscular motions are
altogether out of the power of our
senses & it is only by ascertaining
the changes effected in dead matter
by living beings & comparing those
changes with known analogous ones
in [deletion]dead matter[/deletion] than we can ever
to make any progress in the Knowledge
of the chemistry of life -
Till we are acquainted with the simple
laws of attraction by which two
more principles are connected or separated

[page]45|MS-DAVY-12001-000-00045|dnp20a045pp|70523534[/page]
45
[Tiny ink sketch of face in profile]
To carry on accurate investigations
concerning the action of different substances
on the animal oeconomy, it is essential
to be well acquainted with their
composition & chemical properties.-
otherwise we are in no ways calculated
to discover the effected changes
which is always the end proposed
Hence much of this volume
will be found to be occupied by
chemical investigations which to
the superficial observer appear
unconnected with the phaenomena
of life. It will not however be
paradoxical to assert that it is
from our ignorance of the composition
& properties of inorganic matter that

[page]46|MS-DAVY-12001-000-00046|dnp20a046pp|70523536[/page]
our ignorance of many points
in physiology [unclear]arises[/unclear]. Were we well
acquainted with the composition
of that gas absorbed in respiration
& had we settled our ideas
concerning the nature of heat
such a number of Theories
of respiration would not have
been formed. -
A great variety of coarse
physiological exp[superscript]ts[/superscript] sufficient perhaps
to fill a volume twice as
large as the present might
have been made in half the
time & with 1/10 part of the
labor devoted to these exp[superscript]ts[/superscript]. -

[page]47|MS-DAVY-12001-000-00047|dnp20a047pp|70523539[/page]
47
but whether they would have
established so many useful truths
must remain a matter of
doubt. -
The properties as well as the
composition of the newagent
which may be considered as
the most important fact
of those exp.[superscript]ts[/superscript] - surely demanded
a full investigation & I think
that the exp[superscript]ts[/superscript] on the
Ammonical salts & their
decomposition will do something
x towards clearing the way to
the science of [underline]complex affinity[/underline]
which is in fact. the Chemistry
of life. -

